---
import Doc from '../../layouts/Doc.astro';
import Callout from '../../components/Callout.astro';
import CommandPager from '../../components/CommandPager.astro';
import { url } from '../../lib/url';

const title = 'onboard';
const description =
  'A task-specific orientation brief for a fresh agent or engineer. Under 600 words. The 3 to 5 ADRs that actually apply, the conventions for this area, verification, out-of-scope. Nothing else.';
---

<Doc title={title} description={description} section="commands">
  <p class="doc-lede">
    The surge-staffing command. Every other command in this skill
    <em>produces</em> context; this one <em>consumes</em> it and produces a
    task-specific subset. A fresh agent or a teammate gets exactly the slice
    that applies to the task in front of them, and nothing more.
  </p>

  <h2>Why this command exists</h2>
  <p>
    A fresh agent has zero session history. A new teammate has even less. The
    natural impulse is to dump everything: <em>here is our CLAUDE.md, here
    are all the ADRs, here are the conventions, good luck</em>. That is not
    onboarding. That is a context wall.
  </p>
  <p>
    A good briefing is in what it leaves out. The ADRs that apply to the area
    being touched, and only those. The conventions for those files, and only
    those. The verification commands for that path, and only those. The
    out-of-scope, explicitly.
  </p>
  <p>
    The premise mirrors a finding in the 2026 Anthropic Agentic Coding Trends
    Report: with context formalised in <code>CLAUDE.md</code> /
    <code>AGENTS.md</code>, onboarding times collapse, but only if someone
    curates the slice. That curation is this command.
  </p>

  <Callout label="Read first" tone="ember">
    <p>
      This is the operational form of the "surge staffing" idea from the
      <a href={url('blueprint/#management')}>2026 Blueprint</a>: with
      formalised context, organisations can drop new agents or engineers onto
      a project and be productive within hours instead of weeks.
    </p>
  </Callout>

  <h2>When to reach for it</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Starting a new chat with a fresh agent on a familiar repo.</li>
    <li>Handing a task to a teammate.</li>
    <li>Opening Claude Code on a project after weeks away.</li>
    <li>
      Compacting a long, noisy session. Pause, brief a fresh session, carry
      on with a clean slate.
    </li>
    <li>The repo's context is good but voluminous and the agent does not need all of it.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What it produces</h2>
  <p>One markdown file:</p>
  <pre><code>.context/briefings/&lt;YYYY-MM-DD&gt;-&lt;slug&gt;.md</code></pre>
  <p>Optionally, the briefing is also pasted inline in chat for immediate use.</p>
  <p>The sections:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>What you are working on.</strong> The task, the why, the user-facing outcome.</li>
    <li><strong>What you need to know about this repo.</strong> Three to five sentences. Not the tour.</li>
    <li><strong>Conventions that apply to this area.</strong> Only the rules that touch the files you will edit.</li>
    <li><strong>Decisions worth knowing.</strong> 3 to 5 ADRs with one-line summaries. Plus any negative-space callouts likely to be re-suggested.</li>
    <li><strong>Recent activity in this area.</strong> The last 5 to 10 commits, with dates and one-line subjects.</li>
    <li><strong>How to verify.</strong> Fast and full commands, scoped to the area where possible.</li>
    <li><strong>What's out of scope.</strong> Explicitly. The leash on scope creep.</li>
    <li><strong>Tools available.</strong> Relevant MCP servers, HITL requirements named.</li>
    <li><strong>Where to look for more.</strong> Pointers, not bodies of text.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>How it works</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>
      <strong>Understand the task.</strong> One sentence summary. If you
      cannot summarize, the command pushes back. A briefing for an undefined
      task is a generic dump, which is what this command exists to avoid.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Identify the relevant area.</strong> Map the task to files and
      directories. Should be 3 to 10 paths before continuing.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Pull relevant ADRs.</strong> Scores each ADR for relevance to
      the area. Picks the top 3 to 5. Never pads the list.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Pull recent plans.</strong> Last 2–3 plans that touched the area.
      Skips the section entirely if none apply.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Subset the conventions.</strong> Pulls only rules that apply to
      those files. Prefers already-scoped files
      (<code>.cursor/rules/&lt;area&gt;.mdc</code>) when they exist.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Pull recent activity.</strong> <code>git log --oneline
      --since="14 days ago"</code> against the files of interest. Last 5–10
      commits.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Identify verification.</strong> Fast and full from
      <code>AGENTS.md</code>, scoped form preferred.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Identify relevant MCP tools</strong> with HITL flags called out.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Define out-of-scope.</strong> Two or three bullets. If you
      cannot name what is out of scope, the command asks. The agent's default
      is to expand.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Write the briefing.</strong> Aim 300–600 words. Over 800 means
      the briefing has failed at its job.
    </li>
  </ol>

  <Callout label="The quality bar" tone="mute">
    <p>
      Under 600 words. Every section is task-relevant or omitted (never
      padded). ADRs are listed with one-line summaries, not just titles.
      Out-of-scope has at least two bullets. The test: a fresh agent reads
      this and starts work in under two minutes.
    </p>
  </Callout>

  <h2>Failure modes the command guards against</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Generic context dump.</strong> If the briefing reads like a tour
      of the whole repo, it has failed.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>No out-of-scope.</strong> The agent will scope-creep. Always.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Padding ADRs to 5.</strong> If only 2 apply, the list has 2
      entries.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Briefing without a task.</strong> If the task cannot fit in one
      sentence, the briefing will be a guess.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Related ideas</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <a href={url('foundation/cognitive-debt/')}>Cognitive debt</a>.
      Onboarding speed is one of the success metrics.
    </li>
    <li>
      <a href={url('commands/plan/')}><code>plan</code></a>. Recent plans
      become part of the briefing.
    </li>
    <li>
      <a href={url('commands/adr/')}><code>adr</code></a>. ADRs are the
      single most useful artifact for a fresh agent.
    </li>
    <li>
      <a href={url('blueprint/#management')}>2026 Blueprint: surge staffing</a>
    </li>
  </ul>

  <CommandPager slug="onboard" />
</Doc>
